text: We are the last family that came from Germany in 1952. Undra was the one who assisted the widower. We were the last family that they took to America. I remember it because we have pictures and articles of how my grandparents were so lucky to have been brought to America. I think we were the last family because we had to come earlier. There was a letter that said that we had to come to America. My grandmother came a year earlier. But then my mother took the child and my brother was born in November. Just before that. I think it was because of that. Since we were the last family, when the Hungarian revolution came and they started bringing the widowers from Hungary, we were invited to New York. I remember it so well. I was seven or eight years old. We were standing there with the American flags and we were greeting them. It was especially exciting for me because I was so young. For the first time I was in a hotel somewhere. We received a very warm response. We had interviews. I think we were the last one. We were invited to the Flying Tiger Airlines. I know that we flew over to Ireland. We had to fly over to Ireland because there was something wrong with the propeller. But then they fixed it again. I don't think we were there for too long. Maybe above or something. And then we flew over to New York. So we didn't have that flight history either. Then they immediately brought the buses to Seabrook. Seabrook is a small town in Lona, New Jersey. And it's about three or four hours by bus from New York. And Seabrook because there was a company called Seabrook Farms. Charles F. Seabrook. It was over 30-40 years old. He had built himself a large farmhouse and a cooling plant there. And it was one of the first deep cooling plants in America. It was done with a deep cooling plant. And he needed a job. And he especially needed a job in the summer months when it was just the harvest season. When everything was growing. Before the Estonians appeared there. There were Japanese there. And the Japanese, because America was at war with Japan. The Japanese also put them in storage tanks. Because the Japanese who lived in America. When there was a war in America. They would bury them here. Or they would bury them more. Maybe, you know, connect with Japan. And do some kind of big work. Or I don't know what they did. They were Japanese who lived there for years. They had their own homes. And it was more like a transportation. Not like in Russia. Anyway, they put them in storage tanks. They were told to take what you can carry with you. And they were in storage for a few years. And when the war ended. Then the children, you know. Go now. Live. Search. Of course their homes and places where they had already been. They couldn't go back there anymore. Whether they had been liquidated or sold. Maybe some of them got alone. But basically it was like that. They had to start a new life. So they also came to Seabrook. Because Seabrook forced them to work and live. In the middle of the 1950s. There were about 600 people there. 600 Estonians. In my opinion. I have read somewhere. That at least 1000 Estonians. They moved through there at some point. Some people came there only for a couple of months. And moved on. Maybe they got some contact with other people. Or some better job. But we lived there. I lived there for 12 years. I think that's why my father had a good point of view there. When people came there. They were immediately given a place to live. There was furniture inside. There was food. There was laundry. There was laundry. All sorts of things. They were given a place where they could buy food. What they needed. There was a labor service there. And my friends were there. When I was growing up. Japanese and Estonians. And we were there in school. Like beggars. We were always there in the first classes. We had a tight Estonian life there. It was Estonian Sunday school. Which was held on Saturday. But there was a church component. But also a little bit of Estonian practice. Singing in Estonian. National dance. A little bit of Estonian culture. And Estonian books. Packages to Estonia. It was a big part of life. To get a package to Estonia. I remember how they collected them for several months. What to get. What was needed in Estonia. Does anyone have money. Is it possible to get some extra money. Then of course the money that we had grown up with. Which was not. Which was still in such a good condition. Especially since it was me. And finally I had three grandchildren. Two grandchildren were born in Sibruk. Always a coffee box. Definitely. I don't know where they went. So. It took a long time to plan. How to put it in there. And then finally the packing process. And then some mess around it. To make sure that it was safe. And then the address. And then probably. I don't know if I had to go to Philadelphia. Or. I think I had to go somewhere further. Where to get it. Where to get a package to Europe. Or to get a package to Estonia. When I was five or six years old. I think it was around 54 or 55. I think the first books. Started going back and forth. I remember that. My grandfather. My grandfather Herman Merikani Öte. Who still lived in Tartu. Had changed his name a little bit. He had driven a Merikani. He was a Merikandi. Because. Not to mention. That he was my grandfather's relative. Some five-year-old grandfather. Who was a police officer. And. So. And. And the books always went. So that in the beginning. That book wasn't for my grandfather. You know. At some point. That you could. That you could name. To whom you really write. Because. There was always that feeling. That. That they. That you didn't want. To make people poor. Who live in Estonia. That. Someone. Who has died. And. Who was. Maybe. In the German army. Or in the police. Or whatever. That it is. Or maybe not. And. They had them read. They had them understand. My mother and my grandmother. All the time. And. What had happened. And the thinking here. And. That was. That trial. And. And. And they remembered the time in Estonia. All the time. And what kept me looking. Was. My. Grandmother. My mother. Always had. A different. Different memory. It was. Today. No. It wasn't today. It was today. No, I know very well, you know, such things. The thing with which I grew up, and my mother was, oh, she was such a big fan of communists, Russians, red things, and we didn't want to wear red. That was for sure. And everything in the world that was the cause of red communists, Russians, that was also for sure. But my mother was, well, she was 16 when she left. And plus, she has this thing, I've heard so much about it, that her grandchildren were taken away. Her grandchildren were probably killed right away, very quickly. One father died, and the tree, where he was buried, was broken. The other, those who were taken away from him, there were three children, one was a mother. And that mother died on a train, and at least my mother's story was always that she was thrown out of the train window. She died as a child. When you grow up, that's a big thing. I remember that, yes, friends with whom you grow up, who are not Estonians, for example, Americans, they have grandmothers, they have grandfathers, they have dads, they have aunts, they have relatives, they have brothers. You read children's stories, oh, let's go up to the brotherhood, let's see what old things there are. I didn't have any of those things. We didn't have any old things. We only had the things that we had when we came. We didn't have any old memories of this country. All of our things were in Estonia, our memories, our dreams, our old things, our relatives. So, this coming to Estonia was a homecoming for a person who has never been there, but it was a homecoming. You finally come down from the ship, and then you see that there is this... What was it? It was a wheelbarrow. It was a wheelbarrow. And you are on this side, and you can see through it. It was like a And I immediately walked there, and everyone was standing in line. And I felt them all. I had never seen them in my life, but I had grown up with books, like my grandmother and grandmother. We were talking about them all the time. I stood there, and I said, think. Something was going to happen at the end of the night. Then soon after coming down you saw people in peut. Te lebih, Elmo, Kai, Manti and it was… It was just thunder and lightning. People that you may have grown up with a little bit, but haven't seen in your life, but they are your own.
